{{About|protective coloration}}
{{Good article}}
[[File:Peacock Flounder Bothus mancus in Kona.jpg|thumb|400px|Peacock Flounder ''[[Bothus mancus]]'' demonstrating its ability to [[#Crypsis_by_changing_skin_pattern.2C_colour|change its pattern and colours]] to match its environment]]

'''Camouflage''' is a method of concealment that allows an otherwise visible [[animal]], military vehicle, or other object to remain unnoticed by blending with its environment. Examples include a [[leopard]]'s spotted coat, the [[battledress]] of a modern [[soldier]] and a leaf-mimic [[butterfly]]. Camouflage is a form of visual deception; the term probably comes from  ''camouflet'', a [[French Language|French]] term meaning ''smoke blown in someone's face as a practical joke''.<ref name=camouflet>{{cite web |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/search?q=camouflet |title=Definition of camouflet}}</ref> [[Military camouflage]] is part of a broad area of deception and concealment from all means of detection including sound and radar, and involving non-camouflage techniques such as use of decoys and electronic jamming.<ref name=fm5-20>{{cite book |url=http://cartome.org/fm5-20-toc.htm |title=FM 5-20, CAMOUFLAGE |author=U. S. War Department |year=1944}}</ref><ref name='FM 20-3'>{{cite book | author = Department of the Army | title = Field Manual Headquarters No. 20-3 | date = 30 August 1999 | url = http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/policy/army/fm/20-3/toc.htm | work = Camouflage, Concealment, and Decoys}}</ref>

According to [[Charles Darwin]]'s theory of [[natural selection]], [[Phenotypic trait|characteristics]] such as camouflage that help an animal to survive will tend to evolve in any population.<ref name=darwinoos/>

Camouflage, whether in animals or in military use, can be achieved in different ways, including the apparent opposites [[#Camouflage by mimesis|mimesis]]<U+2014>being seen, but resembling something else, and [[#Camouflage by crypsis|crypsis]]<U+2014>being hidden.<ref name=Forbes>Forbes, P. 2009 p. 50-51</ref> In both cases, however, camouflage is achieved not by actual invisibility, but by not being noticed. A third approach, [[#Dazzle patterning|dazzle]], found military application in the 20th century. 

Camouflage is not the only form of [[animal coloration]] that helps animals to survive. Other [[adaptations]] include [[Aposematism|warning coloration]], non-concealing forms of [[mimicry]] (as when a harmless hoverfly resembles a stinging wasp), the use of bright colours in [[sexual selection]], and the use of [[Biological pigment|pigment]] in the skin to protect against sunburn.

==History==
[[Image:Charles Darwin seated crop.jpg|thumb|upright|75px|left|Charles Darwin (1809-1882)]]
[[Image:E. B. Poulton.JPG|thumb|upright|75px|Edward Poulton (1856-1943)]]
[[Image:Abbott thayer.jpg|thumb|upright|75px|left|Abbott Thayer (1849-1921)]] [[File:Disruptive Coloration by Hugh Cott 1940.jpg|thumb|right|Disruptive coloration by Hugh Cott (1900-1987)]]

Camouflage has been a topic of interest and [[research]] in [[biology]] for well over a century. According to [[Charles Darwin]]'s 1859 theory of [[natural selection]],<ref name=darwinoos>Darwin, C. 1859</ref> features such as camouflage [[evolution|evolved]] by providing individual animals with a reproductive advantage, enabling them to leave more offspring, on average, than other members of the same [[species]]. In his ''[[Origin of Species]]'', Darwin wrote:<ref>Darwin, C. 1859, chapter 4.</ref>

:''"When we see leaf-eating insects green, and bark-feeders mottled-grey; the alpine ptarmigan white in winter, the red-grouse the colour of heather, and the black-grouse that of peaty earth, we must believe that these tints are of service to these birds and insects in preserving them from danger. Grouse, if not destroyed at some period of their lives, would increase in countless numbers; they are known to suffer largely from birds of prey; and hawks are guided by eyesight to their prey, so much so, that on parts of the Continent persons are warned not to keep white pigeons, as being the most liable to destruction. Hence I can see no reason to doubt that natural selection might be most effective in giving the proper colour to each kind of grouse, and in keeping that colour, when once acquired, true and constant."''

In the 19th century, [[Poulton, E. B.|Edward Bagnall Poulton]] studied [[animal coloration]], especially camouflage, classifying different types such as "special protective resemblance" (where an animal looks like another object), or "general aggressive resemblance" (where a predator blends in with the background, enabling it to approach prey).<ref>Poulton, E.B. ''The Colours of Animals: their meaning and use, especially considered in the case of insects''. London, 1890.</ref>

The artist [[Abbott Handerson Thayer]] formulated "Thayer's Law", the principle of countershading.<ref>Thayer, A.H. ''Concealing Colouration in the Animal Kingdom''. New York, 1909.</ref>

In the 20th century, [[Cott, H. B.|Hugh Cott]] worked to persuade the British army to use more effective camouflage techniques, including countershading. For example, he painted two rail-mounted coastal guns, one in conventional style, one countershaded. In aerial photographs, the countershaded gun is essentially invisible.<ref>Forbes 2009, pages 149-150.</ref> His 1940 book ''Adaptive Coloration in Animals'' introduced ideas such as "maximum disruptive contrast" (see illustration), in which streaks of boldly contrasting colour paradoxically help to make an animal or military vehicle less visible by breaking up its outline.<ref>Cott, H.B. ''Adaptive Coloration in Animals''. Methuen, London, 1940.</ref>

== Camouflage by mimesis ==
{{further2|[[Mimicry]]}}

In [[Mimesis (biology)|mimesis]] (also called ''masquerade''), the whole animal (or piece of military equipment) looks like some other object, which is of no special interest to the observing animal or enemy.<ref name="Gullan">{{cite book | title=The Insects | publisher=John Wiley, Blackwell | author=Gullan, PJ and PS Cranston | year=4th Edition, 2010 | isbn=978-1444330366 |url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=S7yGZasJ7nEC&pg=PA512#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>{{rp|512,513}} Mimesis is common in [[prey]] animals, for example when a [[Peppered Moth]] caterpillar mimics a twig, or a grasshopper mimics a dry leaf.<ref name=Forbes />{{rp|151}}

Mimesis is also employed by some [[predation|predators]] (or [[parasite]]s) to lure their prey, for example, a [[flower mantis]] mimics a particular kind of flower, such as an [[orchid]].<ref name=Forbes />{{rp|134}} Such aggressive mimesis has occasionally been used in warfare, for example with [[Q-ship]]s disguised as merchant ships but in fact heavily armed.<ref name="Beyer">Beyer, Kenneth M.: ''Q-Ships versus U-Boats. America's Secret Project''. Naval Institute Press. Annapolis, Maryland, USA. 1999. ISBN 15575000444</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=McMullen|first=Chris|url=http://www.gwpda.org/naval/rnqships.htm|title=Royal Navy 'Q' Ships|accessdate=6 March 2012|year=2001}}</ref>

As an example of mimesis, consider the [[Common Cuckoo]], which is a [[brood parasite]]: the female lays her eggs in nests of other species of bird, always smaller than the cuckoo, one per nest. The female mimics a [[Eurasian Sparrowhawk|Sparrowhawk]]; since small birds then take action to avoid the apparent predator, she then has time to lay her egg in their nest without being seen to do so.<ref>{{cite journal|doi= 10.1093/beheco/arr008|last= Welbergen |first= J. |coauthors= Davies, N.B. |year=2011 |title= A parasite in wolf's clothing: hawk mimicry reduces mobbing of cuckoos by hosts|journal= Behavioral Ecology |volume= 22|issue=3|pages=574<U+2013>579}}</ref> The egg itself mimics the eggs of the host species, reducing its chance of being rejected.<ref>{{cite news | title = Cuckoo in egg pattern 'arms race' | author= Emma Brennand | publisher = [[BBC News]] | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/earth/hi/earth_news/newsid_9418000/9418131.stm | accessdate = 22 August 2011 | date=24 March 2011}}</ref><ref name="ibis2002">{{cite journal|last= Mosk<U+00E1>t |first= C. |coauthors= Honza, M.|year=2002|title= European Cuckoo Cuculus canorus parasitism and host's rejection behaviour in a heavily parasitized Great Reed Warbler Acrocephalus arundinaceus population|journal= Ibis|doi=10.1046/j.1474-919X.2002.00085.x|volume= 144|issue=4|pages=614<U+2013>622}}</ref>

A different, non-camouflage strategy is [[mimicry]], where an animal boldly resembles another animal, typically one that is poisonous or distasteful: it is then easily seen, but avoided.<ref name=Forbes />{{rp|6-42}}

