== Camouflage by crypsis ==
{{see also|Crypsis}}

Crypsis means blending with the background, making the animal (or military equipment) hard to see (or to detect in other ways, such as by sound or scent: for details, see [[Crypsis]]). Camouflage - visual crypsis - can be achieved in many different ways, including:<ref name=Forbes /> 

* General resemblance to background
* Disruptive patterning (breaking up outline)
* Eliminating shadow
* Crypsis by behavior
* Crypsis by changing skin pattern, colour
* Countershading
* Counterillumination

These ways of achieving crypsis are described below.

===General resemblance to background===

Some animals' colours and patterns resemble a particular natural background, for example the [[Peppered Moth]] adult blends in with tree bark.<ref>{{cite book | title=Collins Wild Guide: Butterflies and Moths | publisher=HarperCollins | author=Still, J. | year=1996 | pages=158 | isbn=978 0 00 2200104}}</ref>

===Disruptive patterning===

Some animals, whether predators like the [[Leopard]] or potential prey like the [[Egyptian Nightjar]], have disruptive patterns that break up their outlines with strongly-contrasting markings.<ref name=Disruptive>{{cite journal | title=Disruptive contrast in animal camouflage | author=Stevens, M.; Cuthill, I.C.; Windsor, A.M.M.; Walker, H.J. | journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B | year=2006 | month=October 7 | volume=273 | issue=1600 | pages=2433<U+2013>2436 | doi=10.1098/rspb.2006.3614 | pmc=1634902 | pmid=16959632}}</ref> Disruptive patterns "are characterized by high-contrast light and dark patches, in a nonrepetitive configuration, that also provide camouflage by disrupting the recognizable shape or orientation of the animal".<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.mbl.edu/mrc/hanlon/pdfs/barbosa_et_al_vis08.pdf | title=Cuttlefish camouflage: The effects of substrate contrast and size in evoking uniform, mottle or disruptive body patterns | author=Barbosa, A., Mathger, L.M., Buresch, K.C., Kelly, J., Chubb, C., Chiao, C., Hanlon R.T. | journal=Vision Research | year=2008 | volume=48 | pages=1242<U+2013>1253}}</ref>

<center><gallery>
File:Great male Leopard in South Afrika-JD.JPG|Leopard: a disruptively camouflaged (and [[#Crypsis_by_countershading|countershaded]]) predator
File:Caprimulgus aegyptius.jpg|Egyptian Nightjar nests in open sand with only its disruptive plumage to protect it
File:Podargus papuensis - Daintree River.jpg|[[Papuan Frogmouth]] ''Podargus papuensis'', superbly disruptive
File:Jumping spider with prey.jpg|[[Jumping Spider]]: a disruptively camouflaged invertebrate predator
File:Maskowanie.JPEG|A soldier applying a disruptive pattern to his face; his helmet and jacket are both disruptively patterned
</gallery></center>
{{further2|[[List of camouflage patterns]]|[[Disruptive pattern material]]|[[Military camouflage]]}}

Disruptive patterning is now common in military usage, both for uniforms and for military vehicles. Disruptive patterning, however, does not always achieve crypsis on its own, as an animal or a military target may be given away by other factors including shape, shine, and shadow.<ref name="Sweet">{{cite book | title=Transportation and Cargo Security: Threats and Solutions | publisher=Prentice Hall | author=Sweet, K.M. | year=2006 | pages=219}}</ref>

===Eliminating shadow===
Some animals, such as the Horned Lizards of North America, have evolved elaborate measures to eliminate [[shadow]]. Their bodies are flattened, with the sides thinning to an edge; the animals habitually press their bodies to the ground; and their sides are fringed with white scales which "break up and camouflage any dark shadow line that might fall along the body's edge."<ref name="Sherbrooke">{{cite book | title=Introduction to horned lizards of North America | publisher=University of California Press | author=Sherbrooke, W.C. | year=2003 | pages=117<U+2013>8 | isbn=978-0520228252 | url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zXlLdu3956gC&pg=PA118&lpg}}</ref> The theory that the body shape of the Horned Lizards which live in open desert is adapted to minimize shadow is supported by the one species which lacks fringe scales, the [[Roundtail Horned Lizard]], which lives in rocky areas and resembles a rock. "When threatened, it enhances this resemblance by hunching up its back, an act that displays rather than hides its three-dimensionality."<ref name="Sherbrooke"/>

"Elimination of shadow" was identified as a principle of military camouflage during the Second World War.<ref name="TTT">{{cite journal | url=http://www.lonesentry.com/articles/ttt09/camouflage.html | title=Principles of Camouflage | author=(U.S. War Department) | journal=Tactical and Technical Trends | year=1943 | month=November 4 | issue=37}}</ref>

<center><gallery>
File:Ibexes.jpg|Three countershaded and cryptically coloured [[Ibex]] almost invisible in the Israeli desert
File:Armoured personnel carriers, Eriboll - geograph.org.uk - 1316295.jpg|"Shape, shine, shadow" make these 'camouflaged' military vehicles easily visible
File:Phrynosoma mcallii.jpg|The [[Flat-tail Horned Lizard]]'s body is flattened and fringed to minimise its shadow
File:<U+00D8>velse p<U+00E5> Evjemoen Tropp 4.2 - camouflage nettings.jpg|Camouflage [[Net (textile)|netting]] is draped away from a military vehicle to reduce its shadow
</gallery></center>

===Crypsis by behaviour===

====Decoration, keeping still, lying flat====
Some animals actively seek to make themselves cryptic by using materials from their environment, such as twigs, sand, or pieces of shell to conceal their outlines, for example when a [[Caddis Fly]] larva builds a decorated case, or when a [[Decorator Crab]] covers its back with seaweed, sponges and stones.<ref name=Forbes/> Most other forms of crypsis also require some animal behaviour, e.g., keeping still, lying flat, as in the [[Flat-tail Horned Lizard]],<ref name="HLCS">{{cite web | url=http://www.hornedlizards.org/hornedlizards/hornedlizards_frame.html | title=Horned Lizard Conservation Society | publisher=hornedlizards.org | work=What is a Horned Lizard? | accessdate=December 21, 2011}}</ref> or swaying as if rippled by wind or water currents, as in the [[Leafy Sea Dragon]].<ref name="WWF">{{cite web | url=http://wwf.panda.org/about_our_earth/teacher_resources/best_place_species/current_top_10/leafy_sea_dragon.cfm | title=Leafy Sea Dragon | publisher=WWF | work=The fish that looks like a plant | accessdate=December 21, 2011}}</ref>

Similar principles can be applied for military purposes, for example when a [[sniper]] wears a [[ghillie suit]] designed to be further camouflaged by decoration with materials such as tufts of grass from the sniper's immediate environment.  

<center><gallery>
File:IDF-CombatEngineeringSniper001.jpg|Sniper camouflaged with a ghillie suit and plant materials from the environment
File:Camouflaged crab.JPG|Crab camouflaged with algae from the environment
File:Leafy Sea Dragon.jpg|Leafy Sea Dragon camouflaged by pattern, shape, colour and swaying like the seaweed that it mimics
</gallery></center>

====Motion camouflage====
Most forms of camouflage break down when the camouflaged animal or object moves, because the motion is easily seen by the observing predator, prey or enemy.<ref>Cott, H.B. 1940. pages 141-143.</ref> However some insects such as [[hoverflies]]<ref name="Srinivasan and Davey">{{cite journal | title=Strategies for active camouflage of motion |url=http://rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/259/1354/19.short | author=Srinivasan, M.V., Davey, M. | journal=Proc. R. Soc. Lond. B | year=1995 | volume=259 | pages=19<U+2013>25 | issue=1354}}</ref> and [[dragonflies]] use [[motion camouflage]]: the hoverflies to approach possible mates, and the dragonflies to approach rivals when defending territories.<ref name="NatureNews">{{cite web | url=http://www.nature.com/news/2003/030605/full/news030602-10.html | title=Nature News | publisher=Nature.com | work=Dragonfly flight tricks the eye | date=June 5, 2003 | accessdate=January 16, 2012 | author=Hopkin, Michael}}</ref><ref name="Mizutani">{{cite journal | url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v423/n6940/full/423604a.html | title=Insect behaviour: Motion camouflage in dragonflies | author=Mizutani, A.K., Chahl, J.S., Srinivasan, M.V. | journal=Nature | year=2003 | month=June 5 | volume=65 | issue=423 | pages=604}}</ref> Motion camouflage is achieved by moving so as to stay on a straight line between the target and a fixed point in the landscape; the pursuer thus appears not to move, but only to [[Looming|loom larger]] in the target's field of vision. Numerical simulations show that motion camouflage can be more efficient than classical pursuit (moving straight towards the target at all times).<ref name="Glendinning">{{cite web | url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1691618/pdf/15129957.pdf | title=Motion Camouflage | publisher=The Royal Society | work=The mathematics of motion camouflage | date=27 January 2004 | accessdate=November 25, 2011 | author=Glendinning, P.}}</ref> The same technique could be used for military purposes, for example by missiles to minimise their risk of detection by the enemy.<ref name="Srinivasan and Davey"/> Missile engineers call the constant absolute target direction strategy "parallel navigation"; they have used the strategy since the 1940s, primarily for its efficiency. Bats use it for the same reason.<ref name=Ghose>{{cite journal| author=Ghose, K., Horiuchi, T.K.,    Krishnaprasad, P.S., Moss, C.F., 2006 |title=Echolocating Bats Use a Nearly Time-Optimal Strategy to Intercept Prey.| journal=PLoS Biol |volume=4 |issue= 5 |pages=e108. |doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.0040108}}</ref>

<center><gallery>
File:Hoverfly August 2007-8.jpg|Male ''[[Syritta pipiens]]'' hoverflies use motion camouflage to approach females
File:Nblumhardt - From the Water (by).jpg|Male [[Australian Emperor]] dragonflies use motion camouflage to approach rivals
</gallery></center>

===Crypsis by changing skin pattern, colour===
{{further|Animal coloration|:Category:Animals that can change color}}

Animals such as [[chameleon]], flatfish, squid or [[octopus]] actively and rapidly change their skin patterns and colours using special [[chromatophore]] cells to resemble their current background (as well as for signalling).<ref name=Forbes /><ref name="Wallin">{{cite web | url=http://www.bioscience-explained.org/ENvol1_2/pdf/paletteEN.pdf | title=Nature's Palette | publisher=Bioscience-explained.org | work=Nature's Palette: How animals, including humans, produce colours | year=2002 | accessdate=November 17, 2011 | author=Wallin, M. | pages=Vol 1, No 2, pages 1<U+2013>12}}</ref> 

On a longer timescale, some animals like the [[Arctic Hare]], [[Arctic Fox]], [[Stoat]] (also called E rmine), and [[Rock Ptarmigan|Ptarmigan]] change their coat colour (by moulting and growing new fur or feathers) from brown or grey in the summer to white in the winter; the Arctic fox is the only species in the dog family ([[Canidae]]) to do so.<ref name="Churchill">{{cite web | url=http://churchillpolarbears.org/churchill/arctic-wildlife | title=Arctic Wildlife | publisher=Churchill Polar Bears | work=Arctic Wildlife | year=2011 | accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref> However, Arctic hares which live in the far north of [[Canada]], where summer is very short, remain white all year round.<ref name="Churchill"/><ref name="ParksCanada">{{cite web | url=http://www.pc.gc.ca/canada/pn-tfn/itm2-/2007/2007-01-29_e.asp | title=A hare of a different color | publisher=Parks Canada | work=How Arctic Hares have adapted to Gros Morne National Park of Canada | date=January 29, 2007 | accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref>

Again, similar principles can be applied for military purposes. ''[[Active camouflage]]'' could in theory make use of both dynamic colour change and counterillumination. Simpler techniques such as changing uniforms and repainting vehicles for winter have been in use since the [[Second World War]].

