===Crypsis by counterillumination===
{{main|Counter-illumination}}

Counterillumination means producing light to match the background, notably in some species of [[squid]], such as the [[Sparkling Enope Squid]] (''Watasenia scintillans'') and the Midwater Squid (''Abralia veranyi''). ''Abralia'' has light-producing organs ([[photophores]]) scattered all over its underside; these create a sparkling glow that prevents the animal from appearing as a dark shape when seen from below.<ref name="Abralia with photo">{{cite web | url=http://ocean.si.edu/ocean-photos/midwater-squid-abralia-veranyi | title=Midwater Squid, Abralia veranyi | publisher=Smithsonian National Museum of Natural History | work=Midwater Squid, Abralia veranyi (with photograph) | accessdate=November 28, 2011}}</ref>

Counterillumination is the likely function of the [[bioluminescence]] of many marine organisms, though light is also produced to attract prey and for signalling.

Counterillumination has rarely been used for military purposes. [[Diffused lighting camouflage]], in which light was projected on to the sides of ships to match the faint glow of the night sky, was trialled by Canada's National Research Council during World War II. The Canadian concept was trialled in American aircraft including [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator|B-24 Liberators]], using forward-pointing lamps automatically adjusted to match the brightness of the sky.<ref name="NavalMuseumQuebec">{{cite web | url=http://www.navy.forces.gc.ca/navres/10/10-n_eng.asp?category=183&title=1587 | title=Naval Museum of Quebec | publisher=Royal Canadian Navy | work=Diffused Lighting and its use in the Chaleur Bay | accessdate=January 19, 2012}}</ref>

<center><gallery widths=250px>
File:Watasenia scintillans (rotated).jpg|Sparkling Enope Squid uses bioluminescence to make its underside as bright as the sea surface above it
File:B-24J-55-CO_(cropped).jpg|Forward-looking counterillumination camouflage was trialled in B-24 Liberators from 1943 onwards
</gallery></center>

== Dazzle patterning ==
{{further2|[[Military camouflage]]|[[Dazzle camouflage]]|[[Ship camouflage]]}}

Most forms of camouflage are made ineffective by movement: a deer or grasshopper may be highly cryptic when motionless, but instantly seen when it moves. But one form of 'camouflage' works only when in motion: dazzle patterning.<ref name="Scott-Samuel" />

=== Military dazzle 'camouflage' ===
[[Dazzle camouflage|Dazzle patterning]] superficially resembles disruptive patterning, but has a different purpose. It was used on ships during the First World War, not to make vessels hard to see, but to make their speed, size, range and direction difficult to ascertain by eye.<ref name="Behrens Dazzle" /> Dazzle patterning is therefore arguably (by definition) not camouflage, though it has been called camouflage since the First World War.<ref name="Behrens Dazzle" /><ref name="Stevens Motion Dazzle" /> Non-aligning dazzle patterns may have helped to confuse gunners using optical rangefinders, where two halves of the image had to be aligned by eye to estimate the range to the target ship. However the evidence for its success in naval warfare is mixed.<ref name="Behrens Dazzle">Behrens, Roy R. ''False Colors: Art, Design, and Modern Camouflage''. Bobolink Books, 2003.</ref> Remarkably, some United States Navy camouflage schemes in [[World War II]] attempted to combine disruptive camouflage and dazzle.<ref name="Sumrall">Sumrall, R.F. "Ship Camouflage (WWII): Deceptive Art" ''United States Naval Institute Proceedings'' February 1973 pp.67<U+2013>81</ref>

=== Motion dazzle ===
Motion dazzle is caused by rapidly-moving bold patterns of contrasting stripes, as when [[zebra]]s run from a lion. Motion dazzle may degrade predators' ability to estimate the prey's speed and direction accurately, giving the prey an improved chance of escape.<ref name="Stevens Motion Dazzle">{{cite web | url=http://www.biomedcentral.com/1741-7007/9/81/abstract | title=BMC Biology: Motion dazzle | publisher=BMC Biology | pages=9:81 | doi=10.1186/1741-7007-9-81 | work=Motion dazzle and camouflage as distinct anti-predator defenses | date=25 November 2011 | accessdate=November 27, 2011 | author=Stevens, M., Searle, W.T.L., Seymour, J.E., Marshall, K.L.A., Ruxton, G.D.}}</ref> Motion dazzle distorts speed perception, and is most effective at high speeds; stripes can also distort perception of size (and so, perceived range to the target).<ref name="Scott-Samuel">{{cite journal | url=http://www.plosone.org/article/info:doi/10.1371/journal.pone.0020233 | title=Dazzle Camouflage Affects Speed Perception | author=Scott-Samuel, N.E., Baddeley, R.; Palmer, C.E., Cuthill, I.C. | journal=PLoS ONE | year=2011 | month=June | volume=6 | issue=6 | doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0020233}}</ref> Since dazzle patterns (such as a zebra's stripes) make animals more difficult to locate accurately when moving, but easier to see when stationary, there is an evolutionary trade-off between dazzle and crypsis.<ref name="Stevens Motion Dazzle" /> 

<center><gallery>
File:USS West Mahomet (ID-3681) cropped.jpg|A ship painted with dazzle camouflage to confuse enemy gunners as to her speed, direction, and range
File:Chapman-Zebra.jpg|The Zebra's bold pattern may momentarily confuse predators, especially when many animals are close together and moving rapidly
</gallery></center>

